common:Annotation.common:AnnotationText: In most cases, a legal claim, in many cases tradable in markets, specifying the issuers' obligation to pay principal and, for some instruments, coupon payments, to the holder. However, in the case of "bank prime loan" and "discount window primary credit," the reference is, respectively, to the rate of interest charged on certain business loans and the rate of interest charged on discounts and advances made under the Federal Reserve's primary credit discount window program. Also, "interest rate swaps" refer to an obligation to pay a fixed rate of interest for a specified maturity in return for receiving three-month LIBOR.
